This place is amazing! I love korean bbq as it is, but was pleasantly surprised by the vegetarian options offered here. I'm not actually a vegetarian but I ended up sitting with the vegetarians in our group and I can honestly say I enjoyed all of the food that was served. I'm sure the meat is delicious too, considering the flavor of the vegetarian meat. Give this place a shot if you are nearby. Also try the strawberry soju wine stuff... it tastes like candy but its strong ;)<//Review>

</record></dataset><record>
<Review>I was a little worried at first.  We couldn't find parking and it looked closed.  But we made it!
Fast service,  friendly staff,  and the food is the best K BBQ I've had yet!
Adding to my review...
After a second visit,  I like this place even more! It's a different experience.  It's family owned.  Not by a bunch of quiet Koreans,  but a fun Chicano/Latino family.  The decor is artsy,  the music 80's. The menu is set up a little different and after reading these cry baby reviews,  I can answer their complaints.
The least expensive plate is $12.99 and it's all you can eat. The meat flavors are limited on that meal,  but its all you can eat.
We ordered the $18.99 plate. It came with everything you get at those loud Asian run places.  We shared everything.  And it was all you can eat.  It taste just as good,  if not better,  than any Korean run restaurant.

People are just not used to seeing Chicanos serving K food.  Get over it! Enjoy!< /Review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Response>
None</Response>

< Text>
Straight up my favorite kbbq! This place is a great compromise for my boyfriend and me because I'm vegan and he wants Korean barbecue all the time. There's only two vegan meats but that is a lot more than I can ask for! I thoroughly enjoyed the chickenless chicken because it barbecued well. The marinated veggies were very good and I loved the side dishes! $20 for the vegan barbecue is pretty good to me because vegan meats are usually pretty pricey. Overall, I enjoyed my visit and my boyfriend enjoyed the regular meats.</Text>

< name>
Michael Albert<//name>
<date>1462638736228< /date><rating>5< /rating>< review>
The Coffee Method has some of the best coffee in San Diego. If you want a quality cup of coffee or coffee-drink, come here and you will not be disappointed.

No frills, no strawberry mochacinnos, no dollar menu specials. The comparative drawbacks of this place are those of choosing fresh squeezed orange juice over orange soda: it often takes longer to make and is more expensive.

Another thing is that they are super clean and meticulous about everything: weighing exact amount of beans for each pour over, sampling every batch of ice coffee, and washing every piece of equipment with almost OCD-like frequency. The guy who owns the place might not greet you with a smile or actively listen to your complaining about the weather, but he will make sure your coffee is good.<//review>

<Response>None<//Response><text>Excellent pizza, with a thin New York or thick Chicago crust.  Many other popular Itallian dishes are available. Sauces are full bodied, rich and flavorful, East Coast style. Servings are large.

Most of the menu is available as conventional, vegan, or gluten free. A selection of conventional meats, as well as, vegan "meats" and "cheeses" are offered. There are two menus: vegan/gluten free and conventional. The knowledgeable and friendly servers lead you through the decision making process.  Salads are large, crisp and fresh. Hot, just out of the oven, vegan dinner rolls, at extra charge, as well as, conventional rolls are served.

And, in the tradition of the Chicago pizza restaurants, a carpet of sawdust covers the floor.

The mood is intimate, perhaps a bit romantic. Wine and beer are served. The staff is knowledgeable and friendly.

Free parking in the small lot behind the restaurant and street parking. Wheelchair accessible including bathrooms.<//text></record>

<Name>Ray Holt</Name><Date>1533325069671< /Date><Rating>5<//Rating><Review>I've been coming to The Pizza Cookery for the last 40 years and it's one of my favorite restaurants with consistently excellent food and awesome service.  The atmosphere is family friendly with a good vibe, it's not pretentious or trendy and it has the charm of being a place to kick back and enjoy your meal.

My favorites are the garlic rolls, the chicken wings are better than most wing places, the 5 cheese, BBQ chicken and meat lovers thick crust are heaven, the calamari is tasty and their Antipasto salad is incredible.  They also have a nice variety of beer and wine but the best thing is you're felt rushed to eat and leave like many other busy restaurants.

This is a family run business who does everything possible to make sure you enjoy your meal.  The prices are excellent, the portions are huge, the menu has something for everyone in the family, they use fresh ingredients and they also have a great vegan and kids menu.

There may be more trendy or chic places out there, but if you're looking for a real home cooked comfort food meal that's always a step above everyone else, the Pizza Cookery is the place to go.  It's been our go to place since I was a kid.</Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><resp>None</resp>< Gmap_id>

<review>I tried to like this place, I did. But there were so many warnings signs...

Things I liked:
- The salad.
- Price on individual combo. Less than $10 for a small pizza, salad, bread & drinks is nice!
- Not noisy, big room.

Things I disliked:
- I hate places where I have to struggle to find parking.
- They didn't honor the Yelp Deal I paid for because they said the combo I bought was already discounted (but it's printed on the menu and therefore is not an "offer," but simply a combo much like you would purchase at a fast food joint.
- The Pizza. Sauce killed it for me, tasted like they bought some premade pasta sauce and tossed it on top.
- The floor. When I first visited a pizza cookery, I thought this was cute but later I started thinking it was terribly unhygienic. Do they bother sweeping when something drops on the floor? Can you even tell?<//review>< user_name>

<Time>1410637095394<//Time><Rate>5</Rate><text>So I've lived in Encino for over 3 years now, and I'd sort of given up on finding a pizza place that was as good as my favorite LA joint. I do like Rusty's, but it's no Mulberry Street Pizza.

I dream of the big, floppy slices that you fold in half, with a slightly crispy crust, tangy/spicy sauce, gooey cheese, and lots of garlic. Little did I know that my perfect slice was right there on Figueroa Street the whole time.

It could be that most times I'm down in that area, But I lucked out last Saturday night -we needed a quick bite before a show and every other place was packed. < review>
We're so happy they opened this pace in downtown Concord! Inside looks cute and clean. Service is always nice and you are able to taste test a little sample (love that). The mango flavor is delicious and refreshing for those hot days! I've also had their shaved ice which was long lasting. My ice however wasn't fully covered in flavor, some parts was just ice. I plan to try it one more time just in case that day was just an off day. Overall happy to have this place near by and can't wait to return.<//review>

< text>
Oh my god, one of the best Afghan ice cream in the Bay Area. The ice cream is not an ordinary vanilla but it's a true yellow vanilla that was casted and created from whole milk. The outcome of this product is superb, delicious, tasty and very very cold.

If you like Afghan sheer yakh and don't want to drive to Fremont to pay 15 dollars for some garbage fake Afghan sheer yakh then come to the concord store and enjoy this delicious crafted Afghan ice cream and they also have many more delicious ice creams to serve.<//text>

102912140364292069449</UserId.>
<username>Lixin Jiang<//username><date>1596401218929<//date><rating>1</rating><Text>My baby was born in May and I ordered the panda crate for my baby in July that is when they targeted me as a consumer on Facebook.

By the time the first crate that is designed for 0-2 month baby arrives which was the end of July, my baby was almost 3 month old.

I requested to move forward the shipment date of the second box (for 3-6 month baby) to sooner (Aug) than later (Sept); the first customer service rep told me to come back in Aug to request again, which I did. Then, the second customer service rep told me to change my baby's birthday to an earlier date, which I did.

Unfortunately, neither of these ways actually allowed me to change the shipment date. The second customer service rep indicates that they shipped this way to keep the cost of the shipping down, which doesn't make any sense because the total number of shipment doesn't change regardless of when to actually ship the box.

This company creates a good business concept; as parents, we often don't know which toys are appropriate to babies at different ages. However, I don't understand why they need to be so inflexible in the shipment dates; if you didn't order the crate at the beginning of the line (0-24 months; 2-4 years etc.) they arbitrarily set. Then, all of your boxes would be late for your baby. This is so ironic because they are supposed to fit toys with kids at different age.</Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Response>
